# NGINX:

#### What is NGINX?

---

NGINX is software that runs on a server and handles **HTTP requests** (and other types of traffic).

A single server cannot handle an unlimited number of users/requests at the same time. When traffic grows, we usually add **multiple servers**.

#### How can NGINX handle lots of requests?

One common setup is to use NGINX as a **load balancer**.

- You run **one NGINX instance in front** (the “load balancer”).
- Behind it, you run **multiple backend servers** (your application servers).
- The load balancer **decides which backend server** will handle each incoming request, based on a chosen strategy.

Examples of load-balancing strategies:

- **Round-robin**: send requests to servers one-by-one in order.
- **Least connections**: send the request to the server with the fewest active connections.
- **Geo-based routing**: route users to the nearest server/region (when configured).

This helps your system handle more traffic and improves reliability (if one backend server fails, traffic can be sent to the others).

### **What NGINX can handle too except handling multiple requests?**

imagine one hundred of laptops want to get to see latest posts of news the laptops send request to the server the server send request to the database the database send response to server and  server send data to users . the main **problem is that happened hundreds** of times so what is the solution here? the nginx when the first time take response from database it cache data and then when the second user ask/request the same data the nginx take cached data and send it back to the user

